T-MAZE DECISION MAKING
============================================================
T-maze task: Agent starts at bottom, must choose left or right arm.
Cues at junction indicate which side has reward (with some reliability).

Cue Reliability: 60.0%
  Accuracy: 50.0% (10/20 correct)

Cue Reliability: 80.0%
  Accuracy: 60.0% (12/20 correct)

Cue Reliability: 95.0%
  Accuracy: 45.0% (9/20 correct)

Key insights:
- Higher cue reliability leads to better performance
- Agent balances information seeking with reward seeking
- Demonstrates context-dependent decision making

============================================================
INFORMATION VS REWARD TRADE-OFF
============================================================
Analyzing when agent seeks information (goes to cue) vs exploits known rewards.

Information Preference: 0.0
  Cue visitation rate: 80.0%

Information Preference: 0.5
  Cue visitation rate: 100.0%

Information Preference: 1.0
  Cue visitation rate: 100.0%

Information Preference: 2.0
  Cue visitation rate: 100.0%

Key insights:
- Higher information preference increases cue seeking
- Trade-off between information and immediate reward
- Demonstrates epistemic vs pragmatic value

